14–Female":"1314–Afdød","1337":"1337","1336":"1336","1314":"1314","1356":"1356","1455":"1455","1334":"1334","1453":"1453","1310":"1310","1330":"1330","about 1357":"omkring 1357","1382":"1382","Norwich, Norfolk, England":"Norwich, Norfolk, England","Kimberley, Norfolk, England":"Kimberley, Norfolk, England","Great Yarmouth, Norfolk, England":"Great Yarmouth, Norfolk, England"},"nl":{"1336–":"1336–Overleden","1336–Female":"1336–Overleden","1334–Male":"1334–Overleden","1356–Female":"1356–Overleden","1310–Male":"1310–Overleden","1314–Female":"1314–Overleden","1337":"1337","1336":"1336","1314":"1314","1356":"1356","1455":"1455","1334":"1334","1453":"1453","1310":"1310","1330":"1330","about 1357":"circa 1357","1382":"1382","Norwich, Norfolk, England":"Norwich, Norfolk, England","Kimberley, Norfolk, England":"Kimberley, Norfolk, England","Great Yarmouth, Norfolk, England":"Great Yarmouth, Norfolk, England"},"en":{"1336–":"1336–Deceased","1336–Female":"1336–Deceased","1334–Male":"1334–Deceased","1356–Female":"1356–Deceased","1310–Male":"1310–Deceased","1314–Female":"1314–Deceased","1337":"1337","1336":"1336","1314":"1314","1356":"1356","1455":"1455","1334":"1334","1453":"1453","1310":"1310","1330":"1330","about 1357":"about 1357","1382":"1382","Norwich, Norfolk, England":"Norwich, Norfolk, England","Kimberley, Norfolk, England":"Kimberley, Norfolk, England","Great Yarmouth, Norfolk, England":"Great Yarmouth, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Clifton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the very numerous places called Clifton, from Old English <i>clif</i> ‘slope’ (see   Cliff  ) + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’."],"variants":[{"name":"Cliff","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places called Cliff(e), Cle(e)ve, or Clive, from Old English <i>clif</i> ‘slope, bank, cliff’, or a topographic name from the same word. The Old English word was used not only in the sense of modern English <i>cliff</i> but also of much gentler slopes and frequently also of a riverbank or seashore."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":1,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":46,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":119,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Clifton was born in 1336, in Great Yarmouth, Norfolk, England, her father, Thomas de Clifton, was 26 and her mother, Thomas de Clifton, was 22. She married Thomas Fastolf about 1357, in Great Yarmouth, Norfolk, England. They we